&lt;p&gt;Consider the following premises.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;If it snows, then it is late.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;It is snowing.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;If Joseph were a musician, then Barbara is a bartender.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;If it is late, then it is snowing.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;If it is late, then Barbara is a bartender.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Can we infer the following from them? If we can, name the inference rule being used: Patricia is curious.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Consider the following premises.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;For all x_16, x_16 is a musician if and only if x_16 is poor.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;For all x_16, x_16 will play a game if and only if x_16 is a musician.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;For all x_16, if x_16 were a politician, then x_16 is poor.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;There is at least one x_16 for which x_16 is an artist if and only if x_16 is a politician.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;For all x_16, x_16 will not play a game.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Can we infer the following from them? If we can, name the inference rule being used: For all x_16, x_16 is an artist.&lt;/p&gt;
